
                                                                          Rev. 3

                         |CKBCoding Monsters
                        |BKB ===============

Purpose
|BKB=======

|WKOThe purpose of this doc is to explain how to properly code monsters in
Dakrwind.


|CKBInstructions
|BKB============

|WKOThe first three lines in any monster object should be:

|YKO#include <mudlib.h>
#include <types.h>
inherit MONSTER;

  |WKOThese lines set up the object to be a monster object and will allow
  calls to the monster master object as defined below.
  Additionally, in the reset() function, before calling ::reset(iArg),
  you should enter the following line:

|YKOif(!is_clone(this_object())) return;

  |WKOThis is a memory-saving measure.  The only time this line should
  not be entered is when the monster needs to refer to the master
  object for some reason.

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------


|GKBset_name("name");

  |WKOstring name.  This is a name for the object.
  Also sets the alignment to 0, capitalizes the string you pass
  into set_name and sets the cap_name and short_desc to that, and
  the long description to "You see nothing special.\n"

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_level(level);

  |WKOint level.  This function serves many purposes:

  |BKB- |GKOSets the monster's level according to level.
  |BKB- |GKOSets the monster's intrinsic AC to 10/3 of level.
        Intrinsic AC is defined as that of the monster's "skin"
        (or scales, or hide, or whatever).  This number will be
        added to any armour which you may clone onto the monster
        and make it wear.
  |BKB- |GKOSets the monster's hit points to the max of the result of the
        following equations:
            42 + (Con * 8)
                or
            (Con + 5) * (Con + 5).
  |BKB- |GKOSets the monster's spell points to the result obtained from the
        hit points calculation.
  |BKB- |GKOSets the monster's experience points by getting the number from
        "/domains/darkwind/maincity/adv_guild"


|MKBNOTE: |GKBIt is important to call these two functions first.  Since these
      functions set up many of the monster's stats, if you call these
      functions after you call the ones below, then these functions
      will override those explained below (only if you call them
      afterwards.)

      |WKOI should also note that because these two functions set all of
      the monster's necessary stats, the remaining functions are all
      optional.

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_alias("alias");

  |WKOstring alias.  This is another name for the monster.  It doesn't
  appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_alt_name("alt_name");

  |WKOstring alt_name.  This is another name for the monster.  It doesn't
  appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_aliases(aliases);

  |WKOstring array aliases.  Causes the monster to identify to any of
  the strings in the argument array.

|GKBadd_alias("alias");

  |WKOstring alias.  Adds alias to the array of strings which the monster
  identifies to.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_race("race");

  |WKOstring race.  This is another name for the monster.  It doesn't
  appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.  The race
  is also often used in dir_hooks in rooms as an identifier for
  the monster. See |MKO/open/INCLUDE/monster_race.h |WKOfor currently
  available races.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_short("short");

  |WKOstring short.  This is the description seen when the player
  walks into the room, looks at the room, or glances.
  Sets the short description of the monster to short and the long
  description to the short description + ".\n"
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_long("long.\n");

  |WKOstring long.  Sets the long description of the object to long.
  I added the ".\n" in the LPC line above to remind you that you
  should add the period and newline in the long description
  because LPC doesn't add it in for you.  This is what the player
  will see when they look at the monster.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_size(SIZE);

  |WKOThis sets the size of the monster and is mandatory.  For backwards
  compatablility reasons though, if the line is not in the monster,
  it will default to a size of SIZ_MEDIUM.  Legal sizes are:

  |YKOSIZ_NONE   SIZ_TINY   SIZ_SMALL   SIZ_MEDIUM  SIZ_LARGE  SIZ_HUGE

  |WKOExamples of sizes are:

  |YKOSIZ_NONE: |WKOUsed for monsters that don't leave corpses when they die.
            E.g. Ghosts, Air Elementals, etc.
  |YKOSIZ_TINY: |WKOButterflys, Goldfish, Mice, Rats, etc.
  |YKOSIZ_SMALL: |WKORacoons, Dogs, Cats, Kobolds, etc.
  |YKOSIZ_MEDIUM: |WKOHumanoids (Dwarves, Humans, Elves, etc.), Wolves, etc.
  |YKOSIZ_LARGE: |WKOBears, Lions, Trolls, Ettins, etc.
  |YKOSIZ_HUGE: |WKODragons, Elephants, Whales, Titans, etc.

  It should be noted that if you use SIZ_NONE, no corpse will be left when
  the monster dies.  Anything they are carrying will fall to the ground.
  Also, when a SIZ_NONE monster dies, it will give you a different death
  message than just <You Killed X>.  However, if you set a different
  death message on your monster, that will be used in place of the standard
  one, as usual.

|GKBquery_size();

  |WKOreturns the bit value of the size of the monster.

                    SIZ_NONE   = 1
                    SIZ_TINY   = 2
                    SIZE_SMALL = 4
                    SIZ_MEDIUM = 8
                    SIZ_LARGE  = 16
                    SIZ_HUGE   = 32
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_hp(hp);

  |WKOint hp.  Sets the monster's hit points and max hit points to hp.
  |RKBUsing set_con is preferable, so that in case the hit point formulae
  are changed your monsters won't be wildly out of whack.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_ep(ep);

  |WKOint ep.  If ep is less than the number of experience points gotten
  from "/domains/darkwind/maincity/adv_guild"
  then it sets the monster's experience points to ep.  Otherwise, it
  stays at the value received from "/room/adv_guild.c." |RKOTypically
  this function is only used when you want to make a monster not worth
  anything on death.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_dodge_bonus(bonus);

 |WKOThis number can be positive or negative.  It will make the monster either
 easier or harder to hit in combat.  A monster with dodge bonus 20 would be
 20% harder to hit in combat than another monster with the same stats and level.
  Use this to make the monster better or worse at dodging attacks in
  combat.  It works as a percentage.  Small, quick monsters can be given
  a positive number, while large or clumsy ones can be given a negative
  number.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_al(al,et);

  |WKOint al.  Sets the alignment of the monster to al.  Remember that
  to make a monster evil, you must use a negative number.
  int et.  Sets the ethics of the monster to et.  Remember that to
  make a monster chaotic, you must use a negative number.  If
  you don't set this, 0 will be assumed (ie, setting ethics is not
  required when you use set_al).
  A note with both types of alignment--  The range between -299 and
  299 is neutral, more than 1000 or less than -1000 is very extreme
  (see |MKO'wizhelp 11.1 (alignment and ethics)' |WKOfor more details).
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_ac(ac);

  |WKOint ac.  Sets the monster's intrinsic AC to ac.
|RKODo not use this to just arbitrarily set the monster's ac. If you
don't know when it should be used or not, ask.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_str(str);

  |WKOint str.  Sets strength to str.

|GKBset_int(int);

  |WKOint int.  Sets intelligence to int.

|GKBset_dex(dex);

  |WKOint dex.  Sets dexterity to dex.

|GKBset_con(con);

  |WKOint con.  Sets constitution to con.

|GKBset_wis(wis);

  |WKOint wis.  Sets wisdom to wis.

|GKBset_chr(chr);

  |WKOint chr.  Sets charisma to chr.
  
|RKOThe above functions do not need to be set as the monster's level
will set them up automatically. You will override those numbers with 
these funtions. If you don't know when they should be used, ask.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_move_at_reset();

  |WKOno arg.  Sets move_at_reset (a local int monster variable) to 1,
  which makes the monster pick an exit in its present location at
  random each reset and move in that direction.

  When using this function in a monster, make sure to clone it in the
  room via make_room_unique (see |MKOwizhelp 4.2, coding a room)
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_aggressive(a);

  |WKOint a.  If a is 0, the monster is peaceful.  If a is 1, the monster
  will attack any player that enters the room.  If a is greater than
  1, then a is used as a percentage to determine if the monster will
  attack.  For example, if a is 70 then the monster has a 70% chance
  of attacking a player entering the room, and a 30% chance of leaving
  the player alone.

|GKBint query_aggressive();

  |WKOThis returns the base chance of being aggressive.  It is an integer
  from 0-100 representing the % of attacking on sight.  The value 1
  is never returned, because that is a special value for backwards
  compatibility, and is automatically registered as 100 instead.
  
|GKBset_aggressive_level(a);

  |WKOint a. The variable "a" is a number that represents the player level
  after which the monster will attack. If you set it to 29, the monster
  will only be agressive on players level 30 and above. This function
  is used in conjuction with set_agressive.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_steal(a);

  |WKOint a.  If a is 0, then the monster can be stolen from.  If a is
  1, then the monster cannot be stolen from.  If a is greater than
  1, then the chance of stealing from the monster will be reduced
  by a% (so a thief would have only a 20% chance of stealing from
  a monster which set_steal(80)).

|GKBint query_steal();

  |WKOReturns the value of set_steal.  Note that this function will
  never return 1, because set_steal(1) and set_steal(100) are
  equivalent, and this function automatically returns 100 when
  the monster uses set_steal(1).

|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_viking();

  |WKOno arg.  Gives the monster the viking curse.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_whimpy();

  |WKOno arg.  Will make the monster run away when its hit points get low.

|GKBset_wimpy_cmd(s);

  |WKOstring s.  If set, this will cause the monster to always perform the
  command 's' first when trying to wimpy.  You can use this to control
  which direction a monster attempts to run away.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBload_chat(chance, strs);

  |WKOint chance, string *strs.  Sets the chance that a monster will talk
  each heartbeat to chance, and sets the things the monster can say
  to the array passed into load_chat().

|GKBload_a_chat(chance, strs);

  |WKOint chance, string *strs.  Same as load_chat, but these messages are
  said only during battle.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBload_cmd(chance, strs);

  |WKOint chance, string *strs.  This works exactly like load_chat, except it
  is a list of commands the monster will perform.  You can have an array 
  which includes something like:
  ({"say who are you?","say I'm Bob!","sing"}) rather than having to do
  ({"Monstername asks: who are you?\n","Monstername exclaims: I'm Bob!\n",
  "Monstername sings a song.\n"}) for fairly obvious reasons.  Anywhere
  you place a $N, it will be replaced with the name of a random player
  character in the room, allowing the monster to do directed emotes.
  "kick $N" would cause the monster to kick a random player, for instance.

|GKBload_a_cmd(chance, strs);

  |WKOSame as load_cmd, except works in combat.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_random_pick(r);

  |WKOint r.  Determines if the monster will randomly pick an object from
  the room's inventory.  If the item it picks up is a weapon which has
  a better WC than its current wielded weapon, then it wields the weapon.
  If the item is an armour, and it is not already wearing an armour of
  that type, it will wear the armour.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_dead_ob(ob);

  |WKOobject ob.  Usually this_object() is the object passed to set_dead_ob.
  Use this function in conjunction with monster_died() when you want
  something done when the monster dies.  This function is useful for
  destructing corpses (Like on Stone Golems...)
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_hit_ob(ob);

  |WKOobject ob.  Usually this_object() is the object passed to
  set_hit_ob.  Use this function in conjunction with monster_hit()
  when you want the monster to have a special combat ability.  The
  monster_hit() function should be an integer function which
  returns an amount of extra damage to be done by the monster that
  attack.  The monster will pass its attacker to monster_hit() as
  and argument.  Monster_hit() can be used for many things other
  than simply doing damage.  It can be used to have the monster
  talk, run away, heal itself, summon more monsters, steal from
  the player, etc - what's inside monster_hit is up to the coder.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_init_ob(ob);

  |WKOobject ob.  Usually this_object() is the object passed to set_init_ob.
  If this is defined, the function monster_init will be called by the
  monster whenever it has its init called.  Essentially, this allows you
  to write a function that is executed whenever your monster meets another
  monster or player.  Monster_init should return 0 or else it will
  interrupt the normal init process making aggressive monsters not attack
  and other things.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBcan_put_and_get(n);

  |WKOoptional string n.  If n exists, the monster can put and get things.
  If n does not exist, the monster cannot pick up and drop things.
  Further examples:

       |YKOcan_put_and_get(1);   |WKO// The monster can pick up and drop things
       |YKOcan_put_and_get(yes); |WKO// The monster can pick up and drop things
       |YKOcan_put_and_get(no);  |WKO// The monster can pick up and drop things
       |YKOcan_put_and_get(); |WKO// The monster canNOT pick up and drop things
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_keep_alive(keep_alive);

  |WKOint keep_alive.  This function should be used VERY INFREQUENTLY on
  UNIQUE monsters.  This will not turn off the heart_beat in monsters.
  |RKBDO NOT use this unless the object you are creating REQUIRES it.
  If you are not sure of why you would use this, then DON'T USE IT.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_death_messages(i_died,you_killed);

  |WKOWhen the monster dies it will display the you_killed string to the object
  which killed it and it will display the i_died message to everyone in the
  room.  If these are not set, the default messages will be used.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBcommand("cmd");

  |WKOstring cmd.  Forces the monster to perform the command "cmd".
  The force_us() function isn't always good, because it checks the level
  of the caller, and this function can be called by a room.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_wander(int chance, int time);

  |WKOThis is similar to the move_at_reset function.  It gives the monster
  a percentage chance equal to 'chance' to move.  This chance will be checked
  every 'time' seconds.  For example, set_wander(50,20); would cause
  the monster to have a 50% to make a random move every 20 seconds.
  This allows greater flexibility than the move_at_reset does.
  
  When using this function in a monster, make sure to clone it in the
  room via make_room_unique (see |MKOwizhelp 4.2, coding a room)
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_match(object,functions,types,matches);

  |WKOYou use this to allow your monster to react to what it sees.  Object is
  the object where your functions will be located.  Functions, types, and      |
  matches are all string arrays.  Each must be exactly the same size as the
  others, so you should use allocate() and leave the appropriate elements
  empty.  The following example is Fornay's set_match:

      function = allocate(12);
      type = allocate(12);
      match = allocate(12);

      function[0] = "why_did";
      type[0] = "sells";
      type[1] = "attack";
      type[2] = "left";
      match[2] = "the game";
      type[3] = "takes";
      type[4] = "drops";
      function[5] = "must_be_nice";
      type[5] = "is now level";
      function[6] = "smiles";
      type[6] = "smiles";
      match[6] = " happily.";
      function[7] = "say_hello";
      type[7] = "arrives";
      function[8] = "test_say";
      type[8] = "says:";
      type[9] = "tells you:";
      function[10] = "follow";
      type[10] = "leaves";
      function[11] = "gives";
      type[11] = "gives";

      set_match(this_object(),function,type,match);

      This doesn't make much sense on first glance, but it is fairly
clear if a table is made out of it:
Array       FUNCTION                    TYPE            MATCH
position: Execute this function:   If monster sees:   followed by:

 0          why_did                     sells
 1                                      attack
 2                                      left            the game
 3                                      takes
 4                                      drops
 5          must_be_nice                is now level
 6          smiles                      smiles          happily
 7          say_hello                   arrives
 8          test_say                    says:
 9                                      tells you:
10          follow                      leaves
11          gives                       gives

        Anywhere there is a blank spot, the array has a 0 in it, done
  automatically by allocate().  Every time the monster sees a message it
  will look through the TYPE array, and scan the message to see if it
  contains the TYPE.  It then sees if the rest of the message contains
  the MATCH of the same number.  If the MATCH string is present in the
  message, OR if there is no MATCH at all, then the last FUNCTION that it
  found is executed with the original message as an argument.  For example,
  if Fornay sees the text:
    "Bill takes our taxes"
  First, it will find the FUNCTION 'why_did' at position 0 and save it, but
  won't do anything else because "Bill takes our taxes" does not contain the
  text "sells".  Next, it will go through TYPE until it gets to position 3,
  where it finds the word "takes".  It then looks for a MATCH.  Since MATCH
  position 3 is empty, the MATCH is an "automatic" success.  The last function
  it found was 'why_did' from position 0, so it now does a
  this_object()->why_did("Bill takes our taxes";
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_friends(names, chance);

  |WKOnames can be either a single string or a string array.  Each heartbeat an
  npc has a chance to check whether an npc in its friends list is being attacked
  and join that combat.  The optional chance is a percentage from 1 to 100 and
  defaults to 10.  Use 100 to make friends always join as they did previously.

|GKBset_friend_join_chance(chance);

  |WKOChanges the percentage chance that the npc will check and join its friends
  each heartbeat.  Values are limited to 0 through 100; 0 disables joining.

|GKBint query_friend_join_chance();

  |WKOReturns the npc's current friend join chance.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBcatch_tell(string sStr);|WKO                                                       |
                                                                               |
  |WKOThis function allows you to create responses to your monsters when a specific|
  string is displayed in the environment that the monster is in.  You can hash |
  up the string anyway you like to check for matches and then call functions as|
  appropriate.                                                                 |
                                                                               |
  ***NOTE***                                                                   |
                                                                               |
  It _IS_ possible for a monster's load_chat to get caught and matched in it's |
  catch_tell.  If this happens the mud can crash depending on what you do with |
  the catch_tell.  So unless you specifically desire to simulate NPC's         |
  interacting with each other put an NPC check in the catch_tell before you do |
  anything with it.                                                            |
                                                                               |
  ***NOTE2***                                                                  |
                                                                               |
  One thing to remember is that a catch_tell is only looking for a string match|
  in the environment that the monster is in.  It _IS_ possible to fool a catch |
  tell with an emote or something else along that line.  So you will have to   |
  put in the appropriate object checks as necessary.                           |
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBfollow(str,i,ob);

  |WKOUsing this function allows your monsters to follow other players or monsters
  around the mud.  Str should be the exit message the monster receives.  If any
  positive integer i is passed, then wizards in nohassle mode will be exempted
  from being followed.  Ob is an optional object which, if present, will be
  the only object the monster will follow.  This function is not used in
  reset, but should instead be called through the use of catch_tell as in the
  following example:
  catch_tell(string str) {
        follow(str,1,this_object()->query_attack());
  }
  In this example, the monster is told to follow its attacker if the attacker
  leaves the room, but to ignore any other players/npcs or wizards with
  nohassle mode enabled.

*Important Note*  Additionally, monsters cloned through the reset() of a room
will NOT follow properly.  To avoid this, if you wish to add following monsters
to a room through reset, use a call_out.  For example:
void reset(int iArg) {
::reset(iArg);
call_out("make_monsters",2);
etc
}

void make_monsters() {
   make_object("monster","/players/johndoe/monster",2);
}
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBrandom_clone("filepath",howmany,%);

  |WKOthis function allows you to only clone up equipment for the
  monster a random % of the time. it is important to always
  include how many of that object you want to be cloned, and
  to only use this function inside the reset function in your
  monster. The max % is 50, anything higher than 50 gets set
  to 50.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBmake_random_object("name","filepath",howmany,%);

  |WKOsame as for random_clone, just in the make_object format.
  again, always include how many, and use only inside the reset
  function of your monster.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBmake_unique_and_equip("filepath");
   
   |WKOThis is used when you want your monster to wear or wield your
   unique item the first time it loads. Only use this inside the 
   reset function of your monster.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_switch_chance(d);

  |WKOinteger d.  When fighting 2 or more opponents, this is the % chance
  the monster will decide to switch the target of its attack for that
  battle round.  It causes the monster's attacker_ob and alt_attacker_ob
  to switch places.  If this is not set, it will default to 2%.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_resistance(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc);

  |WKOUse this to add resistances to a monster.  When getting hit by attacks of
  the appropriate type, the monster will take less damage.  A firebreathing
  dragon would probably resist DAM_FIRE, for example.  Use the types from
 |MKO'wizhelp 4.17 (damage types)' |WKOfor a complete list. Please
 also see |MKO/open/INCLUDE/monster_type.h |WKOto see if your monster's race
 already has a resistance by default.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_weakness(TYPE1|TYPE2|etc);

  |WKOAs add_resistance, but it makes the monster vulnerable to that type of
  attack instead of resistant.  As an example, all monster lycanthropes
  are vulnerable to DAM_SILVER.
  
 |MKO'wizhelp 4.17 (damage types)' |WKOfor a complete list. Please
 also see |MKO/open/INCLUDE/monster_type.h |WKOto see if your monster's race
 already has a weakness by default.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_no_block(int blocks)

    |WKOIf you wish to make it so that your monster is immune to a given
    set of blocks, use the set_no_block() call passing the blocks you
    wish to have the monster ignore. For example, to have your monster
    be immune to blindness and paralyzation, you would use this call:
      |YKOset_no_block(BLK_BLIND|BLK_PARALYZE); |RKOYour monster must include
      <blocks.h> to use this.

|GKBquery_no_block(int blocks)

    |WKOUse the query_no_block() call to determine which blocks a monster
    is immune to. If you pass 0 or no argument, you'll get back the
    complete set of blocks. If you pass a bitmap, you'll get back whether
    any of those blocks are in place.

|GKBreset_no_block(int blocks)

    |WKOUse this call to reallow a block to work against your monster.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_no_charm()
|GKBquery_no_charm()
|GKBset_charm()
|GKBquery_charm()

    |WKOUse these as you wish to specify whether your monster can be
    effected by charms type powers like fasttalk, parlay, soothe,
    and anything else in that family of powers.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_death_clone(string sFilePath, status tCloneToEnv, int iQuantity);|WK0

  |WKOAt death, the monster will clone sFilePath. If tCloneToEnv is 1
  or the monster is SIZ_NONE, the object will clone to the environment.
  If iQuantity is not set, it will default to 1. To have any other
  quantity, you must also set tCloneToEnv. If tCloneToEnv and iQuanity
  are not set, it defaults to loading on the corpse, and 1 item.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBvarargs void set_monster_destruct_timer(int iTime, mixed xFunc);|WK0

  |WKOThis function will destruct the monster in iTime seconds. If
  xFunc is defined and is a closure, it will apply the function
  before destructing it. If it's a string, it will tell_room
  or tell_object before destructing it. The monster will be moved
  to the quitroom before destruction, so anything the monster
  has will NOT be dropped in the room. If the monster is in combat,
  the call_out will be called again 30 seconds later.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBvarargs set_variable_level(int iBaseLevel, int iResetTime,
 string sMess, status tCanGoLow, status tOverrideLimit);|WK0
  |WK0This function will change the level of the monster to the level
  of the first player that it encounters, up to 50 levels above its
  configured base level. For example, a level 10 monster will scale
  to level 20 for a level 20 player, but only to level 60 for a level
  70 player. After iResetTime, if not in combat, it will reset to
  iBaseLevel. If iBaseLevel isn't set, it will use whatever level you
  set_level the monster. If iResetTime isn't set, it will default to
  300 seconds. sMess will default to "$N $vlook different." and is a
  room_message that only uses the monster, not the player when setting
  the string. If you set tCanGoLow to 1, then the monster can go lower
  than the level you set_level; otherwise it won't. Set tOverrideLimit
  to 1 only when the monster should preserve the old behavior and scale
  all the way to the player's level without the 50-level increase cap.
  |YK0Eg. set_variable_level(); |000// Will set everything to the default.
  |YK0Eg. set_variable_level(0,60,"$N $vlook BEEFY!"); |000// Will set
    the base level to what was set, reset time of 60 seconds,
    message to looks BEEFY, and won't allow the monster to go under
    the set_level of the monster.
  |YK0Eg. set_variable_level(0,0,0,0,1); |000// Uses the default base,
    reset time, and message, but preserves uncapped legacy scaling.
|BKB-----------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBvoid set_npc_elite(status tElite);|WK0
  |WK0This function will change a regular monster into a slightly
  more elite one. It will add 25% more stats and 5% exp if set. It will
  also add [ELITE] to the short of the monster.
  |YK0Eg. set_npc_elite(1); |000// Makes the monster elite.

